ertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","St.Albans, Hertfordshire":"St Albans, Hertfordshire, England","St Albans, Hertfordshire, England":"St Albans, Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chaney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any one of several places in Normandy, Picardy, or Artois (France) named (Le) Quesnay or Quesnoy, or elsewhere in northern France named (Le or La) Chesnay or Chesnoy. The placenames all derive from Old French <i>chesnai</i> or its Normanno-Picard equivalent <i>quesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (medieval Latin <i>casnetum</i>).","French: variant of <b>Chanet</b>, a habitational name from any of various places called Chanet or Le Chanet, from Latin <i>canna</i> ‘reed’ + the suffix <i>-etum</i> denoting an inhabitant."],"variants":[{"name":"Cheaney","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire, of Norman origin): variant of   Chaney  ."]},{"name":"Cheyney","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Chaney  ."]},{"name":"Cheyne","meanings":["English and Scottish (northeastern Scotland and Shetland): shortened form of   Chaney  , of Norman origin."]},{"name":"Chana","meanings":["Indian (Punjab): Arora and Sikh name of unexplained etymology.","English (West Midlands): variant of   Chaney  ."]},{"name":"Cheney","meanings":["English: variant of   Chaney   with the same etymology as in 2 below.","French: topographic name for someone who lived by or in an oak wood, from Old French <i>chesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (from <i>chesne</i> ‘oak’), or a habitational name from any of several places called (Le) Cheney, e.g. in Haute-Savoie, named with this word. Compare   Chesney  .","French Canadian: altered form of French <b>Chesnay</b> or <b>Chenay</b>, topographic names with the same meaning and etymology as in 2 above, or habitational names from (Le) Chesnay or (Le) Chenay, names of several places in the northwestern part of France, based on Old French <i>chesnai</i> ‘oak grove’. Compare   Chenette   and   Chenier   2."]}]},{"name":"Benedicta","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of   Benedict  , in occasional use in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Benedicte","meanings":["Feminine form of   Benedict  , in occasional use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Benedikt","meanings":["From Church Latin <i>benedictus</i> ‘blessed’.  See  <b>Benedict</b>   ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":60,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":69,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":104,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Benedicta Chaney was born in 1155, in Sussex, England. She married Geoffrey de Noel before 1192, in England. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters."},"et":{"1155–":"1